<br>
Chapter 1 The Beginning<br>
<br>
Two parents stood side by side amazed at the letter they had just received from the Heartwood Master in Kelithin. He was requesting their youngest daughter be sent for training in the skill of Druids.. Mother Tunare had requested it be so. They had no choice in the mater it was send their youngest off to the Solders of Tunare or face shame and outcast amongst their own kind. Mother Tunare requested her..<br>
<br>
Why not Kinned her older brother, more suited to be a ranger. Or her older sister Lillieeanna she hand the sense to stay out of trouble at least...Nothing left to do but send Katreena to meet the Heartwood Master.. Surely he would see she was not suited to anything requiring so much attention, study and practice. She was too easily distracted and tended towards getting lost or adventuring to far into the forest by any small thing, to wander off at a whim. Still there it was Mother Tunare Requested her training..<br>
<br>
Meager supplies were packed.. then to tell Kat she what was requested of her... <br>
<br>
&quot;Mother, I'm here sorry to be late I, I just saw the most amazing thing in the forest and had to go see..&quot; words hung in the air as Katreena looked at her mother, &quot;Is something wrong? You've been crying!&quot; Mother took Katreena's hand and held them to her face. You have to leave I have packed some things here, food, water.. Now is the time for you to be on your own..&quot; Kat looked in stunned amazement, &quot;What, I can't leave. Why, where is everyone?&quot; &quot;Go see your father&quot; was all she could say as she brushed Kat's Hair from her face, tears streaming down, words choked in her throat. She leaned to kiss her child's forehead one last time, could stand the pain no more and turned away. She muttered &quot;Kat, do honor to us all in this and please please stop wandering off&quot; No more was said as sobbing soon turned into a storm of mournful yet stifled cries. Her mother left the room.<br>
<br>
Confused she took the things her mother had packed and stepped into the kitchen.. Her father was there, funny he had never looked so tired or can it be said old. He looked worn from the days tasks. He bid Kat to sit down in the chair next to him. He smelled of herbs and earth. He put his arms around Kat as he stood behind her. Laid on the table was a Note, tear stained and tattered at the edge. He put his arms around her and smelled her hair as he had done almost every day since she was a small girl. &quot;Read this&quot; his said. His shaking hand pointed to the note on the table.<br>
<br>
It is hereby Ordered By the Heartwood Master, Lord and Leader of Soldiers of Tunare, that Katreena will be sent to me for training in the study and art of Druid as soon as possible, in the city of Kelethin As so requested by Mother Tunare. She is to present this note to me upon arrival. <br>
<br>
Eyes now wide in amazement and surprise, Kat looked at the note turned it over and saw the broken seal of the Heartwood Master. Beside the note 2 books and 2 parchments.<br>
<br>
Father now said &quot;One book is a spell book. In which to scribe all of your spells. There are two here to learn on the way to the Heartwood Master. The other you must read and decide which path you are to follow. Mother Tunare will guide you&quot;. Speechless, Kat turned to her father who now had tears welling up in his eyes. &quot;Kat, you are not to continue in your wandering ways this is serious now. What you do from now on will either bring shame or fortune to this family. As judged by Mother Tunare, herself.&quot; He again leaned over and said &quot;Follow what the Master says, do your best, return to us safe when you can&quot; Then one more time admonished her &quot;Please Kat keep your mind on what tasks you must do, no more wandering off&quot;. <br>
<br>
Both Father and Mother now stood at the door, he looking worried and old, she leaning on him for strength and comfort, eyes swollen and red from crying. I looked back and my heart ached to stay, but adventure had finally call me. With that I turned and headed in the direction of Kelithin. <br>
<br>
CHAPTER 2 Heartwood Master<br>
<br>
No sooner had I gone out of sight of my home was I teleported to a deck high above the ground, in a tree. Stunned I stood for a moment turning around and around. <br>
What was this, where was I and how?? My eyes open with excitement I asked everyone &quot;Where is this, where am I&quot;. Most just looked at me as if I were crazy others said &quot;Kelethin&quot; as if I should have known.<br>
<br>
I wandered over this ramp, over that deck, looking at and enchanted by everything and everyone. Never had I seen so many different peoples or shops with so many wares. I had long since forgotten why I was there and who had sent for me.<br>
<br>
I found myself fatigued and lost. It was then I pulled out my food and water, to find the letter.. &quot;Oooh No, I had done it again wandered off&quot;. Angrily I scolded myself. <br>
<br>
I asked for assistance from one and all who passed by me. &quot;Where can I find the Heartwood Mater, please, he is expecting me&quot;. Finally another wood elf saw my plight and came to my rescue. He lead me across swinging bridges, decks and ramps till at last I stood in front of the doors to the Soldiers Of Tunare. I thanked him profusely, and turned to go inside.<br>
<br>
I entered. There inside to greet me were several people most of whom wore scowls upon their faces, staring at me.<br>
I could offer only my humble apologies for not coming sooner. Over to the left stood a man who's wisdom shone clearly in his eyes. He had the look of a great man of experience and nobility. His voice was commanding yet gentle &quot;Come here, young wood elf&quot;. I passed under the glares of the others and stood in front of him and gave him the note with a shaky hand. <br>
<br>
A grin crossed his face for just a second and then the stern look returned. &quot;So, you are Katreena. Let's have a look and see if you are&quot;. The others now spoke up &quot;She was teleported here hours ago Master. One who shows so little respect should be sent back home and shame should be brought down upon her family.&quot; <br>
<br>
The Heartwood Master held up his hand silencing all voices there. He then lifted my chin up so that I looked into his eyes.. My face burned, my eyes welling up with tears, hurt by my shame. He wiped the tears from my cheeks and looked deeply into my eyes. <br>
<br>
I felt everything slip away as his gaze looked deep into the very soul of me. He spoke his word swirling around my head &quot;Ah, although she is not the usual student we have seen, Mother Tunare has requested her to be trained in the ways of the Druid. Who are we to question Mother Tunare. I will be in charge of her training myself&quot;. <br>
<br>
Smiling at me now he said,&quot;Begin your training now, young wood elf&quot;. He gave me a club and showed me how to handle it. Then asked to see the spells I had scribed, showed me the ways in which to cast them. &quot;Go now, practice your skills in the woods near by. Let Mother Tunare guild you in all things. Return to me for future training&quot; he said smiling. He then sent me on my way.<br>
<br>
CHAPTER 3 The Beginning of a Druid<br>
I was still a bit confused by the Heartwood Master accepting me for training, what had he seen in my eyes, my soul? Why had Mother Tunare sent for me? Questions that to this day remain unanswered.<br>
<br>
Quickly and most carefully I made my way to the lift that would take me to the forest floor. The guards I passed on the way would look at me and then dismiss me without another thought. At last the lift, I watched the many people get on and off. I walked forward warily and stood there waiting for the lift to go down. &quot;Humm, how does this work&quot; no sooner had the thought crossed my mind than the lift moved downward. It came to a stop at the ground and I moved off.<br>
<br>
I looked around there and to the left stood a dark figure. I was filled with fear as I passed him. There were several bodies at his feet. His demeanor made me move off all the faster up and over a small hill that opened out on to a clearing. <br>
<br>
There I stood at the top of this hill looking out on small battles others were having with the fauna. Armed with only the club and my spells I too set out to hone my skills. I was so nervous and unsure I looked for a small animal to kill, a bat. I cast Skin of Wood for a shield, surprised it worked. <br>
<br>
I chose my target and swung, eyes closed, hope filled my heart that I would not die. I found myself being attacked back by the creature. It was surprisingly strong and I was fighting not just for the experience, but my life. The battle seamed to take forever, but in reality only a few moments had passed. It was over the bat lay crumpled at my feet, my health all but gone, I had won. <br>
<br>
I picked up my prize and then turned to heal myself. It took all the mana I had and I was only half healed. I sat to regain mana and watched again the battles around me.<br>
<br>
The action was for the most part non stop as young wood elves, half elves, gnombs and more all chasing down their targets, each one having their own skill to learn. Some clumsily, like myself, fought. Others like dancers with grace and precision. I watched and was soon practicing the skills of the more graceful ones, hoping somehow to attain their skills. <br>
<br>
Many times throughout the day I repeated the steps.. Cast shield, fight and kill my target.. heal myself and rest.. again and again for hours collecting small prizes of pelts, wings, bone chips, rusty weapons and more. I would break only to sell those treasures and lighten my pack. <br>
<br>
Soon exhausted I sat down to look at the red book my father had given me. The words seemed a threat to me more than a choice, it was clear the path that I would take.. I through the book in a fire and hoped no one would find the likes of it again. <br>
<br>
Then back to the lessons that only doing battle would teach me. I was close to the edge of the clearing on the far side when a gracious wood elf stopped at my side. She smiled at me, &quot;young wood elf you have done well, but you need clothing and a better weapon. I have been watching you and your courage has been shinning brightly&quot;. She then gave me a savants cap and cloth gloves. I knelt at her feet and gave humble thanks for her generous gifts. Then as quickly as she appeared she left. <br>
<br>
There I stood mouth agape, eyes wide in wonder and my heart leaping for joy. I carefully inspected the items, &quot;Oh my, I thought I would never be able to repay her, and what was her name&quot; stunned and shocked by this act of kindness I felt tears welling up in my eyes. I took a break and decided to go to the Heartwood Master and see if I had need of further training. <br>
<br>
I stood on the lift to the city above, waited and waited puzzled I jumped up and down, got on and off, what was this, it had always just worked never before had it not.. I asked &quot;Is the lift broken?&quot; &quot;No&quot;, came the reply. &quot;Oh&quot;, I said shyly looking for the reason it would not move. Then a young gnome came up laughing &quot;Silly girl, you press this button and there is one at the top. Where are your brains&quot;. My face must have been very flushed, &quot;I'm sorry&quot; he said more kindly &quot; thought everyone knew about this&quot;. &quot;No&quot; I said softly and shook my head we have nothing like this at home. The lift took us up and stopped, I thanked the gnome and quickly moved away from his sight. &quot;Stupid girl&quot; I scolded myself &quot;Why couldn't I have figured that out for myself&quot;.<br>
<br>
Off to the merchants and then to the bank I carefully went. I put every copper I had collected in my account it had grown to more money than I had ever seen 8 gold pieces in all.<br>
<br>
I then went to see the Heartwood Master. I opened the doors and went in quietly as I could not wishing to draw attention to myself. Another young elf was there training so I sat and watched carefully the lessons he was learning.<br>
<br>
Soon it was my turn and I stood before the Man, the master, trainer. I had gained enough experience to train for 10 sessions. He asked &quot;what do you want to know young Katreena. You have done well and I am pleased with your efforts&quot;. I stood there, choices? &quot;Oh my&quot; I was and wasn't ready to learn.. what should I do? I excused myself and left quickly.. outside I sat and thought long and hard, I prayed &quot;Mother Tunare lead me please, I don't know what it is I need to know&quot;. Tears welled up again in my eyes, &quot;I was surely not meant to be a druid&quot; I thought.<br>
<br>
I passed the Champions of Faydark and went in thinking &quot;Maybe just maybe there would be one there that could help me, give me a bit of advice&quot;. Mother Tunare had lead me there with kindness there were those that would help. &quot;You first need to buy these spells. See here, these are the ones you need&quot; she said kindly. <br>
<br>
I quickly went to the bank, pulled out every last copper and returned buy the two that I could afford, Snare and Burst of Flame. I quickly found a quiet spot to scribe them in my spell book and put them to memory. Then off to the Heartwood Master I had need for training now. <br>
<br>
I went in, stood in front of him and asked for training in Alteration and Evocation.. as well as more 1 hand blunt. &quot;You have chosen wisely, Katreena.&quot; he had the look my father got when I had done something that pleased him.<br>
<br>
Then he said &quot;It is time for you to quest young druid.. We may not use blades they are forbidden by Mother Tunare I wish to rid the land of these vile things. Therefore, I need you to bring me 1 rusty blade each of the following: A bastard sword, a short sword, a long sword and a broad sword. You will be rewarded when you return with these items. Go Katreena and bring pride to us the Soldiers of Tunare, young druid&quot;. I vowed not to fail, and left ready to try my new spells and hone my skills once again.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Chapter 3 In Training<br>
<br>
<br>
I stopped at the bank to place the few coppers left in my account. I was moving through the city with light easy steps, more quickly than ever. However, I must have been lost in my head for I was lost again, &quot;Was it left here or right? over this ramp or that bridge?&quot; I wandered around again over and over trying to find my way. <br>
<br>
I came upon a large barrel and thought &quot;I needed to refill my water I opened it up and it said combined. I put my waters into the barrel and did just that. They were gone,&quot; This could not be good&quot; I had no water, now. I scolded my self for my ignorance &quot;Foolish girl, you still haven't learned anything&quot;.<br>
<br>
After much roaming, I found my way to a lift down. Not one that I had been at before, but a lift just the same. &quot;Oh to feel ground under my feet again&quot; I wished to myself. Then before going down I shouted out &quot;Anyone have extra water. In desperate need of water, Please&quot;. <br>
<br>
A young man stepped up to me and asked what had happened to my rations. &quot;What have you done with your supplies?&quot; Shy and embarrassed I explained my fool hearty attempt to get water from the barrel. He smiled and said &quot;Don't be to hard on yourself, you learned a valuable lesson, yes? You will not repeat it again, I hope&quot; &quot;Oh, yes&quot; I said shyly. He then looked at my equipment, &quot;Here I have plenty of water and food and you will need this as well&quot;. He gave me water and food, 5 platinum and a Great Worn Staff. &quot;You know what to do with these right&quot;. <br>
<br>
Stunned and stuttering &quot;Oh, yes I do believe so. You are so kind,thank you very much, sir&quot;. I bowed to him as he left me there. My heart ached with joy as another kind person had done me a great favor and expected nothing in return. &quot;Was this Mother Tunare?&quot; It seemed to me to be so.<br>
<br>
I return to the floor of the forest and proceeded to use my new spells and skills. It was wonderful the snare spell meant no more chasing the Burst of Flame gave me the advantage I so badly needed in my battles. The things I chose became increasingly easier to kill. <br>
<br>
Every once in a while I would take out that Great Staff and polish it, hold it swing it. Clumsily at first, I knew then the direction of my next training sessions with the Heartwood master. <br>
<br>
It was on one of these breaks that I stopped to look around. &quot;Oh, my where am I? The lift was right there, no over there. Damn!&quot; I had done it again I was lost. This time nothing seemed right. No trail, no lights, no familiar land marks and it was getting dark and starting to rain.<br>
<br>
Just then a most wondrous and beautiful thing flew by, a small, multi colored dragon. So delicate and enchanting I followed, not thinking of the dangers I might be wandering into. <br>
<br>
It was not long before I came across a horrid looking creature large sulking shoulders, blue grey green in color I had seen smaller ones in the meadow earlier but this was much larger and had a look of some wild sick animal. I hailed him hoping him to be friendly, he turned and grunted then charged. I knew not to waste time, but turned and ran, but to where, which way &quot;Just run&quot; I said &quot;pray that I might live through this&quot; <br>
<br>
I stumbled into the mist of a camp of them &quot;Oh, No&quot; I heard myself cry. I saw others on a hill fighting more of them I Yelled for Help. Only to have two more beast turn and start to chase me as well. I was in deep trouble now and could only run to the groups doing battle there. <br>
<br>
It was then a strong looking huge man stepped in swinging and axe that was much bigger than I was. He took down one quickly and then another. He took some blows so I healed him quickly as best I could. The last of the beast fell, He bent down and collected the loot from the dying bodies. He stood up and Looked at me, your way too young to be hunting in these parts, miss. His smile turned into a chuckle as he inspected me. Your a child, come follow me I will take you back to a safe place. <br>
<br>
I followed closely like a puppy tagging along after him. I felt safe behind this Warrior,if that is what he was. His face bore blue paint and he clothes where of ring mail. &quot;Here we are young one. You go that way to the safe area&quot;. He pointed to the Lift. &quot;Oh, don't I get a hug for my heroism&quot; Shyly I stood up on my toes hugged him modestly. &quot;Here beautiful one&quot; He gave me a necklace of cat eye, &quot;You should have many such gifts, to match your beauty&quot; I blushed &quot;Thank you so very much I said, you have been a true hero. May Mother Tunare Bless your travels&quot;. I turned quickly and ran to the lift. <br>
<br>
Finally in the new recruit training area again I went to work, killing skeletons embarrassed by my early adventure. I had a lot of stress to work off but unfortunately this area did not provide enough experience to further my training and not enough challenge to keep my interest. I soon wandered off on a trail. Thinking that I would be somewhat safe this way and I may find something new. <br>
<br>
Sure enough I came upon a strangely built formation 4 spires and it was in the middle of no where. I looked around and asked about the meaning of such a place. Someone near by mentioned this was a teleport ring?? &quot;Yes I asked eagerly and what or who does it teleport&quot; I had heard many people shout for a teleport but not once had I guessed that this is what they met. I stood in the center and shouted &quot;Teleport?? nothing happened humm how did this thing work&quot;. The few that were there started laughing, finally someone explained that this was the wizards teleport ring and only wizards could use it. <br>
<br>
Again Embarrassed, I set off on the trail back to Kelethin, or so I thought. I found at the end of a trail a beautiful city in the side of a mountain. I spent the day wandering, talking with all who would answer my questions. I found a person who wanted mail delivered to the bard guild in Kelithin it seemed a small task and there was mention of a reward for my efforts. Greedy for any chance for experience or cash I took on this task.<br>
<br>
Running along the trail back to Kelethin I once again happened upon the Beautiful flying drake. I couldn't resist the temptation to follow so off I went. &quot;Oops&quot;, not a good idea because I was soon lost. &quot;Which way had I come from&quot; Now along comes a big Orc Centurion, I hid hoping he would not sense me there. Luck would have it that he passed by me so close that I could smell the stench of his breath. <br>
<br>
Okay I was lucky that time Mother Tunare was with me and keeping me safe, but I was still lost. Wandering the woods this way and that I was soon in danger again. This time my skill in hiding would not protect me. I cast Snare on one of the Orcs hoping to buy time only to be brought down by another. &quot;How many hits had I taken one, two maybe three? Then I was a dead druid&quot;. This would become my rule in battle. <br>
<br>
Mother Tunare returned me to the Newbie Training area as it is called. I now had to find my body and retrieve the most precious gifts. But which way.. I had food and water restored but otherwise I was as naked as the day I had arrived here. Okay I was at a city named Felwithe I could start there. Let see I had taken a trail to the &quot;Wizard Spires&quot; then on the the City.<br>
<br>
Soon I was there I headed out on the trail I though I was last on then wandered in circles, ever larger looking for the small body that was mine lost in the woods. I came upon a young man in robes and asked it he had seen my body? <br>
<br>
&quot;No, but I will help you find it&quot;. He said grinning at me. &quot;Follow me, I am a Necromancer and have a talent for locating corpses&quot;. &quot;Oh?? Thank you for your time and help I replied&quot;, Off we ran through the forest. &quot;He asking me how I had lost my life being so young&quot;. I of course replied with my usual &quot;Foolish young girl looking for adventure and finding it&quot;.<br>
<br>
Soon we were standing beside my body I quickly collected my things again giving thanks for his kindness. I asked what I could do to repay him &quot;Nothing, it has been a pleasure to help you. Now go that way back to Kelethin&quot;<br>
He pointed &quot;and be careful you should stay close to the druid ring in the Newbie area till your skills have matched your curiosity for adventure&quot;. <br>
<br>
Off I went attentively, looking into each shadow for any dangers that may be lurking there. I made it back safely to the newbie area. &quot;Okay, boring as this might be to be here I would not venture out till I had more training which required more experience. Oh, Yes! I have that letter to deliver to the Bard Guild&quot; I quickly made my way there turning in my letter to the requested person receiving experience and silver for my efforts. <br>
<br>
Returning to the forest floor and to the druid ring there I took up battle with the skeletons that roamed there. Finding on them the requested Swords for the Heartwood Master's quest. I quickly had three of the 4 swords and experience was climbing, too. <br>
<br>
It seemed that I spent days hunting for that last sword I started thinking that perhaps I should just buy the last one and be done with the quest. But, no one would sell me one &quot;Is it for the Quest they would ask?&quot; &quot;Yes&quot; I would reply, &quot;Then go kill skeletons you need the experience girl&quot;. So I did again and again hunting down and killing them each time it became easier and easier. Finally the Sword dropped from one of them and I quickly returned to the Heartwood Master to turn them in. <br>
<br>
It was here that I had my very first meeting with a thief. I had tried to give the swords to The Heartwood Master only to have them drop on the floor a stranger was behind me and picked them up as they dropped. I was crushed, I had worked so hard to collect them and now he stood there ignoring me and simply took them I begged and pleaded with him, to no avail. <br>
<br>
Nothing left to do but to go do the quest again. It took me several more days to compleat the quest. This time I was extremely guarded in giving them to the Heartwood Master. A Scimitar was my reward as well as experience. <br>
<br>
I now could train with the Master again. This time I chose two hand blunt and one hand slashing. As well as furthering my casting skills. I was now in my 5th Leaf and could buy more spells as well. Purchasing all the spells for my level I could now Camouflage, cure poison and disease, Invoke Lightning and Gate. Oh now I could travel quickly back to where I was bound any time.<br>
<br>
I allowed myself some brief practice time with the new spells then I was off to join a group, my first. I went to the area called the Orc Lift and shouted that I was ready to join a group, No response came back. <br>
<br>
I followed the trail back over the knoll there where Orcs crossing here and I chose to take one on. The battle was intense My new spells worked well victory was soon mine. I was Meditating regaining Mana when I saw a young bard pulling I asked if he needed help and much to my delight He invited me into a group of three others. We stayed there pulling down from the tents of Orcs on the hill I healed,d sowed, snared and cast damage spells. We all split the loot and experience. I was so thrilled with how well and fun it was to have someone else to group with. Again and again I would join a group in this area whenever possible and soon was fighting up on Orc hill. <br>
<br>
However, I again became tired of the same old same old and was wandering off on my own. Kat, if you will stay and fight with us you may join but if you wander off take on your own battles don't pull them to us when you can't handle them. So I would venture farther and farther from the camp and would find myself in trouble. I died many a times learning the lessons that fighting alone would teach me. <br>
<br>
I was to be a group fighter, I didn't have the strength the warriors did, or the speed to make a get away that the bards seem to possess, or the powerful damage spells that the casters had. So, a lone fighter I was not meant to be or was I? At the time I had just turned 7th leaf.. <br>
<br>
I was unsatisfied with the killing of the Orcs and decided to leave Kelethin. Time for me to travel and explore I would come back one day, but not now. <br>
