I had shouted out &quot;Any one need a talented druid to help eradicate these stupid poor Orc beast&quot;. Oasis of Mar was the location, the days had wore on me. I was trying of the non stop march that the Orc warriors had day in and day out. <br>
<br>
I soon joined a Group of like minded fighters and there we stood at the side of the lake facing off time and again with one after another of these Orc beast. Filthy beast, they had a camp in my home land Greater Faydark. I had come to seek adventure and again ran up against the massive on slot of an invasion. <br>
<br>
In this group is where I first met the exotic Barbarian Luner. Who too, was far from her home Halas, and her companion a mysterious Man known as Shugar.<br>
<br>
Turns out she had been here longer than I and more experienced. She shouted out &quot;Stay close to the lake when we pull those beast in. Don't want the whole hwy to come down on us&quot;. I had been standing up on the ridge to watch the puller bring in another of the large beast. 3 came in all at once and the fight was non stop. <br>
<br>
When those were disposed of I sat down to meditate, regain my strength and mana. Mother Tunare was with us this day. I looked briefly around and asked if any needed food or water. Shugar asked and I gave, seemed only right, he started to pay me and I shook it off &quot;No, to keep you here is payment enough at the moment. We can't lose one as talented as you&quot;. <br>
<br>
Soon it was time to get up and fight another round with 3 or 4 more Orc Warriors. Again, Lunar reminded me not to stand up top the ridge. I bowed to her and gave thanks that she was watching me well.<br>
<br>
I have always been a curious sort, I would between breaks in the battle go explore. This had more than once gotten me into trouble. I must admit my shameful ways here and say that I should have learned not to do this in 18 seasons. But alas, I was born more interested in the spirit of adventure than the fame, fortune and glory others seek.<br>
<br>
I was glad that Luner had sensed this in me and brought me back to my senses.. &quot;Incoming&quot;, she shouted. <br>
<br>
Our group broke apart after a long day of fighting. Some needed to camp, some to go to Freeport, others on their way to lands unknown. <br>
<br>
Luner and her companion stood by me as she was preparing to go and said gently, &quot;Are you in a guild?&quot; &quot;No&quot;, I replied. She then explained that she and Shugar had admired not just my fighting skill, but the way I had watched every ones back. That and the easy acceptance of being told what to do without question and the care I had shown for all who where with me that day. <br>
<br>
She said &quot;You would be a fine addition to our Guild, The Bronze Dragon Fellowship&quot;. We sat and talked a while about the guild and the way she spoke of it made me hunger for my family and home. I was given directions on who to see and applied for membership. I bowed to her and Shugar and bid them fair and safe journeys. I then turned my thoughts to home and the bitter loss of my family, I was so lonely. <br>
<br>
It didn't take me long to decide to join this Guild. I needed family, I had been alone too long. It would be good to see a friendly face once in awhile in my travels.<br>
<br>
Chapter 2<br>
<br>
I could go back to Greater Fay, but I had not had my fill of adventures. And there Mother Tunare was whispering &quot;Come see this land I have made for you, come get lost in all the glory and wonder&quot;. How could I go home when there was nothing there for me now.  The there was the call to adventure with each person I met, I found tales to fantastic to belive. <br>
<br>
I had needed rest so off to East and West Commons to hunt. However, in my rush to have green grass under my feet and trees over my head, I had forgotten how sad this land made me. The Great Bears and Kodiak that roamed would have bodies scattered about. Here to the beloved brother Wolf would fall to the uncaring hand of those who could not see through a druids eyes. <br>
<br>
I would shout out in anger &quot;Do not kill these blessed beast please!&quot; To no avail, I was met with laughter and contempt for my beliefs. I tried to explained that the least they could do is give thanks for the great battle that had been fought with such bravery by the Great Bears. But my words seemed pointless to those who chose to hunt them down. I only stayed here long enough to fill my packs with Greater and regular Lightstones. Then I was off to the Great Plains of Karana again.<br>
<br>
I would have stayed in Kithor Forest had it not been long ago over taken with evil and dangers that I was not yet trained to take on. Then there were the bitter memories that this wood held the secrets that only I knew of.<br>
<br>
 Through the city of High Hold Keep, where battles raged so fiercely here on three fronts that the citizens had to stand at every corner. No rest for me here, I was not comfortable with the humans who lived in this realm and city life was not suited to me.<br>
<br>
Down the long trail to East Karanas where this time I discovered gnoll reavers who used my brother Wolf for evil. At night the undead would rise and use them to battle the living. I could not find it in my heart to kill them even if they had been turned from the Light of Tunare. <br>
<br>
I needed to stop at the Druid rings there in North Karana for training and spells. Then off to the Great Bird Avaik, who for some reason had built a city somewhat like Kelethin. I was hopping that this would add a save to my wounds and scars. I longed for my family and the forest of Greater Faydark. I was mistaken, I felt only more lonely and bitter. <br>
<br>
I pressed onward down into Lake Rathe. There I had come across an lonely man who was camped by himself, a hermit of the lake if you will.<br>
<br>
I attempted to share and give comfort to this lost sole, only to have him attack again and again. I had another season under my belt when I left and he was not changed. <br>
<br>
From there I did not venture far. Here there are Great Bird Avaik Guards, who for some reason feel they must guard. What I am not sure as they never once took up battle with anything. I thought, well I may as well attempt to hone my skills and new spells with these great birds. I knew they would provide the challenge.<br>
<br>
Chapter 3<br>
<br>
I had spent a few days here grouping with like minded adventures. This is where I first met him, a Warrior, a Human with a grin as wide as his shoulders and as bright as his armor. He had a few seasons on me the bore the guild tag of the Bronze Dragon Fellowship. I asked him how he liked the guild. Turns out his sister was Lunar, a Stormheart, too. He said he would speak with the guild and see what he could find out about my acceptance. We fought well together off and on over the next few days and spent time talking of adventures. <br>
<br>
He then asked a strange question, Marriage. I knew him only a short time, and had enjoyed our time together. But this was not what I had expected. after all, I gently told him &quot;I could not accept the kind offer that my heart belonged to Mother Tunare. I had a taste for adventure. I did not see my self with any one, nor could I take on the responsibility of keeping out of trouble myself. That it wouldn't work any way He being a Human and I a Wood elf&quot;. We parted friends. <br>
<br>
Then the great day came when I was accepted into the guild.<br>
Lady Kelee invited me. I was enthusiastic to say the least<br>
I now had a family everywhere, a friendly face to greet.<br>
<br>
Back to Lake Rathe I traveled. There he was again, he was not in the guild anymore. He said simply that something personal had happened, however, he was to soon to rejoin. I asked no questions and expected not explanation. He looked at me and said you need a better weapon. Lets go to Runnyeye and Get you a staff. I blushed and asked &quot;Are you sure?&quot; He explained that He would get some more people to help out.<br>
<br>
Well, true to his word there he was with friends from the guild awaiting my arrival and he had his tag back. Greeted me with that grin and said &quot;Lets get you a lens. I can use some bi armor, too&quot;. We set off and down into the depths of runney eye there we fought side by side with other guild members whom I cannot remember but only thank here. It all seemed like a game to him. He and I would joke and laugh as we fought side by side. This was the first time in along time the loneliness in me seemed to subside.<br>
<br>
Finally the elusive Broxx showed up the battle fought and won. I was given the lens and sent on my way with well wishes. It was a great day and one of upset as well. For as I turned in the lens little did I know you had to have good faction with the gnomes. So I didn't get the great Staff Of Observers that day.<br>
<br>
Chapter 4<br>
<br>
I in my disappointment went home to Greater Faydark. There I met a Mage by the Name of Elemental she had happened upon the Great Bloodforge Hammer and passed it to me once she had heard of my trials. <br>
<br>
There was a message from Him asking what I was doing. I sent word back that I was in Butcher Block resting. To my surprise He seemed to have dropped what he had been doing and came all the way from who knows where to help my new friend Elemental by passing on some Orc belts. I found myself admiring and thinking fondly of him as he had come out of his way and was so generous with no thought of repayment. I thought he would have moved on after I had said no to his desire to be a husband, but there he was and then gone on his way again just as quickly.<br>
<br>
I once again travel to South Karana this time to try my hand at killing the Tesh Mall Gnolls that had an underground city there, an Evil Race. I had taken to heart the Code of the Bronze Dragon Fellowship and knew it was my duty to eradicate evil wherever I found it.<br>
<br>
I was on the move again, adventure called me north. Low and behold, there I had met up with him again in North Karanas. He invited me to hunt bandits by the river. I found myself glad to see that familar grin. He was now such a good friend and partner and easy to hunt with. We all to soon disbanded camp and I went one way he another.<br>
<br>
Time passed and I wandered the lands looking and exploring every part I could, seeking adventure everywhere.<br>
<br>
Much to my surprise, there was a message &quot;Need help. In Kunark. Can you come. Caddil&quot;. Now how could I not. So off I went to see what I could do to assist him. There he was at Fironia Vie dock. That grin, and as always, happy to see me. He had lost his stuff somewhere in Lake Ill Oman and needed to find it. As we ran he teased me about being his druid and pet. I thought this was a nice friendly tag for me. I teased back with friendly banter which had now become our way of chatting. &quot; Okay, how did you lose it this time?&quot; &quot;Goblins&quot;, he said &quot;Nasty things, but good experience&quot;. I looked at him and thought, Oh my.. Do I have enough skills to pull this off. He directed me to the place and, &quot;Yup&quot;, there were goblins there. Unlike I had never seen. Our first encounter was a disaster only to have to go back an retrieve my stuff as well. Again I asked&quot; Where is your stuff&quot;, &quot;Somewhere here&quot;, he replied.<br>
<br>
Into a tunnel we went, I had cast superior cameo on both of us and hoped that these exotic creatures could not detect us. Down farther I went asking him &quot;Where are you?&quot; He had gone ahead of me answering back &quot;I cant see. It is too dark&quot;. Only then did I remember he was Human and thought, &quot;Oh yes, Humans cant see in the dark like Wood Elves&quot;. I took my Bloodforge Hammer out, finally found him and gave it to him. I said &quot;Now lets get this done&quot;.<br>
<br>
We roamed the caves with danger and adventure everywhere. This was just what I had needed, my heart pounding fast my senses on edge. <br>
<br>
At last we broke through into a clearing and there was his stuff. The adventure done I was happy he had his stuff, but sad that we would be going separate ways again. He gathered his things up gave me back my hammer and thanked me heartily. He invited me to stay and fight with him but I to timid said &quot;Nay,sir. I am not ready to deal with unknown lands as these now&quot;. Again we parted better friends. I had had fun, scared but fun. <br>
<br>
Chapter 5<br>
<br>
The Next time we met was at the Wedding of Nef and Lunar.<br>
There he was boisterous as ever. &quot;Kat, where did you get that shield&quot;. I had been to Mist moor and had been given a shield after fighting and losing a random draw. I will save that story for another time. &quot;Can I use it&quot;, he asked I timidly thought this over and said &quot;Yes, go ahead&quot;. He and Eldo couldn't resist the temptation to duel.<br>
<br>
Joyous and happy was the occasion and when it was done everyone was headed to the arena. Caddil invited me but I declined, as I had some far traveling to do. He once again bowed and gave me back my shield. &quot;See you around my pet&quot;.<br>
<br>
Chapter 6<br>
<br>
A few more seasons I hunted in familiar lands. Looking for the excitement I had found in Kunark. There was some to be had in Rathe Mountains and going deep into Feerrott. I even so bold as went into the temple of Cazie Thule. It offered the chase, but I felt I was not quite skilled enough to venture very deep there.<br>
<br>
I had finally felt comfortable enough with my skills to travel back to Karana, to the lake Caddil had me venture to. &quot;Ah, the prize, to explore the new land&quot;. The temptation to great not to go, with tails of dangers and adventure filling my mind I soon found myself there.<br>
<br>
Caddil had mentioned Sarnaks earlier, that sounded good to me, off I set. Once again looking for a group to join. I had been there only a few days, when there he was &quot;Hiya, Kat, How is my pet&quot;. Soon we were fighting side by side like always he boasting about this kill or that skill,. Showing me his latest trophy and armor. I by his side casting getting to know what he wanted and when. He laughing at me when I couldn't get it right and cheering me on when I did. <br>
<br>
&quot;Coming Kat, lets go do...&quot; I would cringe thinking &quot;I'm not skilled enough for this&quot;. There I found myself in the thick of battle. Almost always hiding behind Caddie, but there. I leaned to trust him as he would say &quot;Don't run, I will get it&quot;. I would close my eyes hard and pray knowing that it only takes 3 hits and I'm a dead druid. <br>
<br>
When I would open them there he would be grinning &quot;Got It.&quot;<br>
I would check out and see what damage I had sustained and more often than not it was him who needed the heal.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ya got food, Kat.&quot; I had learned early on this man traveled fast and thought little of comforts. He only carried a small supply with him. I always had food and water and was more than willing to share. That, and his grin could have been his calling card.<br>
<br>
Always, every time he met me he would want to know what I had been doing and listened to me intently. I know I must have been a bore, as I'm sure his adventures where more danger filled, pressed with much more excitement at every turn. I found myself envying him, to be so strong and sure of every move. I wished I had had that confidence in my skills. <br>
<br>
He would check my equipment out and tell me I needed this item or that and would soon bring me gifts and surprises. I a little more than overwhelmed I eventually asked &quot;Well, what is it you would like to quest after&quot;. He would shake his head and laugh &quot;I can get what I need&quot;, boasting again. I feeling a bit foolish for even attempting to follow in his foot steps. I told him then that he could help me in my quest to fill my needs, but that for him to spend hard earned rewards was not to be, at least on me. I didn't like being indebted to any one. And in my pride especially not to him. <br>
<br>
I had been hunting the Mighty Giants in Frontier Mountains and had been so lucky as to pick up a Forest Loop. A much prized item. Caddil also was here once again bragging how he had a new axe and that he owed a fellow guild member for it. He was slowly paying him off. At last, I saw my chance to pay him back for his much to generous gifts. I in my sly ways discovered who it was and offered the Forest Loop as payment for Caddil's axe, a deal was done. I felt much better for the act. Pridefully I thought &quot;Now we were even and I would no longer be in his dept&quot;. <br>
<br>
Chapter 7<br>
<br>
Next time I saw him He had grouped at the Sarnak Fortress all day killing the nasty looking 3 horned lizard creatures. I had a season up on him now and he was determined not to let that stand for long. I joined him and found that he was grouped with a fellow traveler named Calicer. <br>
<br>
Caddil and my teasing of one another had become all too familar. I would tease &quot;All Hail the great and mighty warrior Caddil&quot; and he would bow and say &quot;that's my pet&quot; Then kiss my cheek in jest. This put Calicer off a bit, not knowing that it was all in fun between friends. I joked that Caddil would kiss him to, however that Caddil was a Mans Man. That being said even he joined in the jest. <br>
<br>
Between battle we spoke of adventures and Calicer asked about the Guild. It was Caddil who invited him to the planned event that night. We made arrangements to meet later on as I was to be the transportation for that evening so we could all attended a Fight Night. <br>
<br>
We arrived and Caddil rushed in leaving Calicer and me at the gate. I unsure of exactly what was going on stood outside timidly peering in, amazed. I told both of these men &quot;To go right in. I was going to watch from here&quot;. Caddil returned, only shrugged those big shoulders and grinned at me. Calicer followed him in. <br>
<br>
Soon Calicer was taunting me. Asking me in, saying that he didn't know who to challenge and I would be safe with him. I thought &quot;Okay girl, get your bucket of guts out and show our invited guest what it means to be a Bronze Dragon Fellowship member&quot;. In I went nervously looking around exploring every corner of the massive arena. <br>
<br>
Up on the platform Calicer stood looking around. So I hit him with a spell. Snared him down and started a battle laughing and saying &quot;You did want to do battle?&quot; He came after me and off we went my health going down fast. I ran for the gate to regain my composure and health. I though &quot;Now,that wasn't so bad for this Wood Elf. Lets go do it again&quot;. I teased Calicer until he returned and we had another go around. At last he conceded, I think he just let me win. He stopped fighting back and begged for mercy. I told him I would not kill him but let him live with the shame that I had bested him. <br>
<br>
I thought this was fun and soon was up on the platform again this time looking for a fight. There stood Banlaen, he hit me with a spell that sent me reeling. When I gained my senses back, he said teasingly &quot;TAG&quot;. Oh, what a challenge, I could not leave it unanswered. Little did I know he could disappear from sight and reappear in the blink of an eye somewhere else. This was going to be much harder than I thought. Around the arena I chased him finally caught him outside the gate. I snuck up and &quot;TAG&quot; I was off in a flash. On through the night the laughter never stopped. Finally it was time for me to go and Caddil came by and said &quot;Alas my sweet timid pet has become a bloodthirsty killer&quot;. He grinned and pecked my cheek bid me farewell.<br>
<br>
Chapter 8<br>
<br>
The next time I met Caddil he said to me &quot;I'm going into the gorge today to hunt Evil eyes, want to come&quot;. Knowing full well that I desired Polished Bone Bracers. &quot;Oh&quot;, I shyly said. &quot;Well, if your already headed in that direction I would like to come&quot;. He laughed &quot;I have a druid I need to get a pair for so we will get you a pair, too&quot;. <br>
<br>
I wondered who was this druid but didn't ask. I was a friend nothing more and it wasn't my concern. Still I found myself a little uneasy about this other druid. Hummm<br>
<br>
We spent a good part of a day camping the Evil Eyes. Loot was good and we did get a pair of the bracers. Then finally Caddil had to leave. I tried to give those to him for his druid friend. but he said &quot;Naa, I'll come get another pair soon enough. You need them now&quot;. <br>
<br>
So I made up my mind to return to the area and get the second pair by myself if need be. I was well into camping the Massive Eyes and able to take them down one at a time by myself, who would have known. <br>
<br>
I had one bracer and needed only one more to help this druid of Caddil's. That is when here came Caddil strolling in with another woman at his side &quot;Come on&quot; he said &quot;we can get the other one quick enough and then be off to Runnyeye to get some Bi armor&quot;. He was right of course with their help we soon had our prize. He said &quot;Kat, can you hold those for me? I will get them later&quot;. Off he went with his new friend to do battle in Runnyeye again. <br>
<br>
Chapter 9<br>
<br>
I had received a call to The frigid City of Halas a young Barbarian there needed guidance in the ways of Tunare. A shaman who still had to gain control of his skills. I took what I could to help lead him in the service of Mother Tunare herself.. <br>
<br>
I joined the young Shaman at what they Called Orc Wall. yes even here the evil Orcs had a stronghold. <br>
<br>
 His name was Slaor, strong and intelligent but quiet, he seemed unsure of his calling.  For many days I would talk of Mother Tunare and her ways. He would ask what it was that Mother Tunare wanted from him, I could not answer as I only knew that she had her reasons. <br>
<br>
 I would help him do battle explaining how to best defeat this enemy or that. Talking of the spells that he would best find useful and in what situation.  We became fast friends, I felt stirrings in my heart that frightened me. At night we would sit by the fire that he has built and I would tell him of the adventures I had had the lands I had seen. He would wrap me up in hides from the great Polar bears.  We would sleep very close together for warmth in this frozen land it was the custom. <br>
<br>
It was on just such a night that he asked about the guild and I spoke of family and the friendships I had made there. He was interested in joining, so I gave him the appropriate information. He was kind and gentle sole, I was sure would do well in the Bronze Dragon Fellowship.<br>
<br>
After our discussion we had bedded down for the night when I felt his arms wrap around me.  I felt a desire that frightened me even more I wanted him to hold me.  Once he was asleep I quietly packed up and left.  How could I want any man in that way. No it was best if I just left.<br>
<br>
Soon the Bronze Dragon Fellowship called him into service. I was asked to give him transportation to Sir Koraf for the invitation into the guild. I knew once he bore the tag of the Bronze Dragon Fellowship he too would find a family that would help and support him well.  <br>
<br>
He meant my eyes with hurt in his, but said nothing and asked no questions. I was thankful for this and was able to treat him like a brother and friend.<br>
<br>
I brought Slaor to West Commons after that to give him a taste of green land. Turns out it was just in time for a Bronze Dragon Fellowship Raid into the depths of Beholden. A place of Undead and stench. I always hated these places, they made my skin crawl with the evil and unnatural things that lived deep inside, nothing good could come of it. Here I once again met up with Caddil and Banlaen I introduced Slaor and our newest member. They took to him as one of the family.<br>
<br>
Chapter 9<br>
<br>
Caddil was on a quest, eager to get the Thex Mallet found in Befallen. I was again listening to him boast that he could clear all the floors, no problem. There I was timid and unsure never having adventured down below the 1st door, that was many seasons ago. He lead me down into the depths explaining the quest in detail. I kept wondering &quot;Why he would even think of me to help in this after all He could do all this himself&quot;.<br>
<br>
Well that wasn't quite right. He did need me to give the note that was taken off of Gix and give it to Skeleton Lrrod. We did this several times without success. Banlaen even came to help. I said &quot;This must not be the correct note. We may need to have a Dark Elf who has turned to the light to help with this&quot;. After much asking around I found one who was willing to help. Giving him the instructions to asked Gix for the note then give it to the Lrrod. We three would jumped down the well to destroy the Commander Windsong&quot;. It worked and the quest was done.<br>
<br>
It was here that Caddil told me of the Paw of Oppola. Once again he had sparked the adventurous spirit in me.<br>
<br>
He said we can do this quest together &quot;You and I, we will get 2 of everything&quot;. &quot;Okay, no problem&quot; I said. He wasn't ready to do the quest just yet, though. <br>
<br>
I was eager to have that prize. I had many messages over the following week asking what I was doing. I would send him a reply &quot;Camping for the rings&quot;. &quot;Blah&quot;, he would answer &quot;Come join me. We can do that some other time&quot;. If he had only known the temptation he created in me, but my desire for the Paw is greater this time. <br>
<br>
Finally I was so bored awaiting the Mummy Gylnok to appear, I thought I would go crazy. Sure enough I would have had it not been for the kindness of passers by who gave me encouragement to go on. In those last hours a familar face came by, Banlaen said &quot;You need to rest and get out of here&quot;. I argued &quot;No,I would not give in to the temptation to leave&quot;. Resigned he asked what he could do to help. I said I needed one more ring from Black Borrow, away he went.<br>
<br>
Just after that The Mummy Gylnok haunted befallen again and I was successful at destroying him, found the precious platinum ring. &quot;It was Mine at last&quot;. What a relief. Just then a note came from Banlaen saying he had the sliver ring in his hand. I quickly joined him in Qeynos Hills we together traveled into Qeynos to finish the quest and received the Paw of Oppola. It was done at last. <br>
<br>
So with that done I went back to the Land of Kunark to see if the Paw was worth the price I had paid. For being bound to one place so long with only stories from those who took pity on me during my vigilant hours. It was and more, to my surprise, my skills and mana had improved much. It was time to make up for the lost experience. <br>
<br>
I was eager for adventure again.. A friendly face of one who had giving me encouragement while I had camped was here, Gorsha. He and a friend said &quot;Come join us. We will kill Sarnak together&quot;. All to soon his friend left us to do battle alone. I was much more seasoned than Gorsha and thought I would help family and friend to gain more experience, by watching out for him. That turned my thoughts to Caddil, how many times had he done the same for me. I cleared my mind and prepared to do battle with Sarnaks.<br>
<br>
Chapter 10 <br>
<br>
A call came from Mildikin a gnome tinkerer who needed to teleport into Steamfont and then out to West Commons. A very special event was to take place within the guild, a fireworks display. I needed to now be a mule, to carry bags of equipment from one area to another and collect bat wings, was my order. And who was there as well, Caddil &quot;Hey can't let you have all the fun&quot; he teased. He had made room in his packs to also carry finished fireworks. Along came Slaor, who too, would help. He had been hunting just to the west killing Minotaur in the caves close by. I sent a message out to tell everyone of the event as I hunted down batwings for Mildikin. Soon we could carry no more and off we went to Antonica. There we would separated and then rejoin for the event later. <br>
<br>
We all joined up at the tunnel that ran from East Commons to North Ro. It was time to set off the fireworks and rejoice in the Bronze Dragon Fellowship. It was a special night for Wysh had announced his engagement and introduced all who where there to his fiance. <br>
<br>
A break in the fire works occurred when a duel had broken out. A friendly one by the looks of it, between Wysh and Caddil. I was busy handing out fireworks to those late comers and not really paying attention to the action. The next thing I knew Caddil was gone in a flash. He sent me word that he had quit the Bronze Dragon Fellowship, he was extremely hurt and angry. <br>
<br>
I felt my heart plummet. Oh not to see him again, not to see his shoulders set in battle, or to see his grin, or to hear him say &quot;Kat, you got some food. Or, &quot;Can you get me too ??&quot; I pondered the situation long and hard. Who else knew me so well, who would be my hero when I got myself lost and in trouble. I didn't realize how much I had come to rely on him, or how much I looked forward to his banter. What now, what to do. To quit the Bronze Dragon Fellowship and follow him. That would be fool hearty indeed. Yet that is what I wanted, but NO you don't just quit your family because you are hurt. The arguments went on in my head for days. I belonged to a Family and you don't quit family. I had to look at this sensibly. <br>
<br>
It was then I received word &quot;Come join me in Sol A. We will adventure together, again&quot;. My heart took fight as I ported into Lavastorm. There he was &quot;See my new leggins, I&quot;I'm dead sexy&quot;. I joked back &quot;We'll see, you might be dead, soon&quot;. Off we went down into a new world. He no longer angry confided in me that he had been wrong and acted to hastily in anger. There was that grin that so endeared him to me. <br>
<br>
I asked myself what this is, I felt stirrings within my heart. Confused I thought this will never work you know a Human and a Wood Elf. Were is the sense in that. <br>
<br>
Sure enough we soon where both dead in the depths of Sol A. Having to fight our way back to collect our things once again. Finally he said &quot;Lets get out of here I'm tired of a losing battle&quot;. Off we went to High Hold to kill the evil Pickclaw that lived under High Hold Keep. &quot;Good experience&quot; he said. <br>
<br>
When we had tired of that off to Runnyeye to get BI armor for Slaor. Even now he supported the guild. Even if he never was able to rejoin again. It was not common for one to leave the guild three times and be invited back.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, I do not love him&quot;. I once again said to myself this will not work I am a free spirit who belongs to Mother Tunare. Then the answer so clear came. Hadn't Mother Tunare set him in my path time and again. Wasn't it he who had encouraged me to adventure even farther than I ever had. &quot;Come join me&quot; his words echoed in my mind. Wasn't it he who protected me from harm when danger was at it's greatest &quot;Stand Still, don't run I will taunt it off&quot;.. again his words echoed. Didn't this serve Mother Tunare wishes for me. Were these not acts of one who loved me. <br>
<br>
So on my way back from delivering Caddil's gifts to Slaor I sent him word that if the offer still stood I would be more than honored to join with him in marriage. That to be his pet was not enough anymore I had come to want to be his partner in good and bad in all that he has to share. He then gave me the news that &quot;Yes, yes he would take me for his wife&quot;. As if the moment couldn't be more happy he told me that he was to rejoin the guild. That High Lord Rashek had been so moved by those who pleaded in his stead, that Caddil would have one last chance to be a Bronze Dragon Fellowship member. <br>
<br>
Chapter 12I was looking for a wedding gift for Cadill, my search had taken me to Qeynos Hills but to no avail.  I ran into a Monk that needed a Teleport from the pass there to the West Common Druid ring, I was happy to oblige him. He was dressed meagerly and said he had been killed in West Commons.  I understood all to well the dangers he would face running there. I quickly gave him the Spirit of the wolf, the Strenght of Stone and Skin like Steal then one last spell to teleport us to West Commons. He was so greatful and tried to pay me I just waved him off saying this is a Gift from Mother Tunare Serve the Light in all you do and pass on the kindness shown to you kind sir.<br>
<br>
Passing back through West Commons I heard a friendly bid of good night. Turning to find where it came from I heard him ask &quot;Kat is that you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, Slaor it is I, Katreena. I heard you yell out good night to the guild and came quick as I could&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;Why did you not answer back?&quot; He said worried.<br>
<br>
&quot;I wanted to talk with you in person&quot; I replied.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, this sounds of a serious note&quot; He said. <br>
He stopped in mid sentence and looked into my eyes and must have seen the pain there, that I was trying so hard to hide.<br>
I sensed anger rising in him, but he kept cool and asked me &quot;Come share some of my wine and warm yourself by my fire<br>
Katreena, tell me of your journeys&quot;.  A chill went down my spine as these words were spoken. Isn't that what he had bid me so many seasons ago, in the cold dark night of the<br>
frosty tundra.<br>
<br>
&quot;Slaor&quot; I began &quot;I wish I had more time to spend with you now. But I can only stay a short while&quot;. I was so uncomfortable and I sensed that he could feel the uneasiness that was in the air.<br>
<br>
&quot;Tell me now the truth what is it that has shaken you? You have always been honest with me Kat do not stop now&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;I had hoped to spare you of this news, Slaor. We need to finish what is between us and our unspoken love for each other.&quot;<br>
<br>
This caught him by surprise and he flinched but said nothing.  I moved close to him now and laid my head on his chest.  This way I couldn't see his eyes when I knew the hurt that I would soon be causing him. That hurt would be reflected there in his eyes.<br>
<br>
 &quot;I have known of your love for me for some time now. Ever since the time we were together in Everfrost.&quot; I said sadly<br>
<br>
&quot;You left so suddenly and with out a word&quot;. He interrupted<br>
<br>
&quot;Please don't stop me, this is hard enough&quot; I begged. Taking a deep breath I continued. &quot;I realized that I loved you too, Slaor. And that is why I left&quot;. I felt my eyes sting as they filled with tears. Tears that now made it down my cheek and dropping onto Slaor's chest.  I gasped for breath as my throat tightened with emotion. &quot;I was too young for love of this depth. My heart and my head were spinning in chaos. I was to bitter about the past. To many losses.  You being a Barbarian and me an elf? I had to run. I had to have time to think&quot;.<br>
<br>
I continued, &quot;I spent time in meditative prayer. As well as adventuring, but you were always there on my mind.  I had sorted my feelings out hopping that you would always be a friend&quot; <br>
<br>
 Now came the hard part as I paused for courage to go on.  &quot; I had met a warrior before I was sent to your side by Mother Tunare. He has a lust for adventure such as none I have known.  In the beginning I thought of him as only a friend as well.  But, things have changed between us, they have gone beyond those feelings of friendshiped. I now have deep feelings of love for him. This time I am ready, I no longer fear what it will mean to be his wife. You see Slaor I am to be wed in 2 days time&quot;.<br>
<br>
I felt his chest fall his breathing become labored as he whispered &quot;Go on, tell me who this brave warrior may be&quot;.<br>
<br>
My heart ached for him as I slowly said &quot;Do not be angry with him, Slaor. Please.&quot; I said through falling tears. &quot;You know him well.  Caddil&quot;. <br>
<br>
His body stiffened, his voice angry and surprised &quot;What? That bastard, my best friend!&quot;<br>
<br>
I now had to look into his eyes, to help soften the blow to his heart. I lifted my head and met his gaze. I pleaded &quot;It's not his fault that he did not tell you. It was I who asked him not to say a word to you. I wanted to spare you the pain&quot;  <br>
<br>
He stumbled on his words and thoughts &quot;I, I told him of my love for you.  He has been with you all this time. How could I have be so blind&quot;<br>
<br>
Again I pleaded &quot;Please, Slaor. Please turn your anger towards me, for I made him give his word not to tell you. You know him to be an honorable man. He would never break a promise. This has hurt him as well as you and it is all my fault&quot;.<br>
<br>
He looked at me resigned and said &quot;I wish you two all the happiness in the world&quot;.  I softly said &quot;Thank you, Slaor.  Thank you.&quot; <br>
<br>
We sat in quiet reflection of the past news drinking wine and staring into the depth of the night. The wolves seemed to echo the sadness that was between Slaor and I now. <br>
<br>
