<br>
I awoke that morning with Mother Tunare shinning down on me. Everything seem perfect, ah but there was still an uneasiness in my body. An excitement and anticipation of the day's events. <br>
<br>
I spent the afternoon brewing a batch of vodka trying to calm my nerves. Then to run some errands here and there just to keep myself busy. Last minuet plans for the evenings events. &quot;Humm, do I have everything&quot;, confused and jumpy I turned to Frontier Mountains to join friends in Killing Giants. <br>
<br>
&quot;I just need to keep busy, just till this evening&quot;. I would sit down and quickly stand up as if sitting on bees. The tension was mounting. Time took forever to pass to evening. But, soon I was teleporting those who chose to attend the ceremony to North Karana for the long trek down to Lake Rath. What time, where, what Island, all became a blur to me, hugs and best wishes where said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Finally everyone was there, or were they? I looked around for his face. Passing out flowers to the brides maids and Clover to the Best man, I spied him. There it was that handsome strong form, those shoulders set firm and there the most gentle face and that all to familiar grin. <br>
<br>
Everything fell from sight except for his face, the grin, and his eyes, looking lovingly at me and saying &quot;I do&quot;. Joy so now filled me to overflowing, was there anything except us at that moment. I was now this brave young warriors wife, partner and lover, bound forever, by spirit, heart and sole. Blessed by Mother Tunare Herself.<br>
<br>
Nothing else mattered that evening as I lay in his arms, strong, safe and loved. How did I get to be so lucky I wondered. Then my head laying gently on his chest, his breathing comforting me, the gentle beating of his heart whispering &quot;I love you&quot;. I soon fell into a gentle sleep, happy and contented. <br>
<br>
Chapter 2<br>
<br>
Days turned into weeks that passed all to quickly.  Love has a tendency to blure things that way.  Our love and joy was only made deeper and more intense as we discovered more openly about who each person really was.<br>
<br>
Every day I found myself missing him if he left for only a few hours.  Was love like this burning so brightly meant<br>
<br>
  And Now the Bad News<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
It was a bright morning, one of many that Mother Tunare had blessed. The air was crisp and fresh, the grass was sweet smelling, the trees swayed gently in the breeze. Since our wedding I was never more content or happy and everywhere the world seemed to be agreeing with my mood.<br>
<br>
I had been busy for most of that morning running here and there and had yet to meet up with my handsome husband who had been fighting late into the night the night before. I heard a whisper in my heart &quot;Where are you my love, I have missed you. Come to me&quot;. It was Caddil in the Overthere calling to me to share in an adventure. Joyfully everything else was forgotten as I made my way to his side.<br>
<br>
Once there I saw him not as a man but a wolf, someone had cast wolf form on him. He was strong and very much the leader of the pack, even in that form I loved him dearly. He came and nuzzled me and I scratched his ears and smiled down at him. His eyes were smiling and even in that form there was that grin. I never would have believed the depths my love had or could grow in that short amount of time. <br>
<br>
We fought side by side for hours, doing battle with new and exciting creatures of the Overthere. Kunark Rhinos, Thorny succulents, Stone catcher Cockatrices and there again were Sarnaks. Our group was small Caddil, myself, Sister Trimom, a Cleric Toxichat conversation was light and easy. <br>
All too soon Caddil spoke up and said that he had some business to attend and it was time for us to disband and go our separate ways. I chose to stay and continue fighting I was enjoying the day so much.<br>
<br>
I fought by the side of another warrior, Ergo was his name for the rest of that day. Many others would come and go and my role in the group would change from a healer to a fighter many times. Experience was good and I was content to explore this new land. <br>
<br>
I heard my love call to me over the hours and we would chat lightly &quot;How you doing, are things going well?&quot; Whispers of I love you were said throughout the day, confessions of how deep, sweet loving words shared only between him and I alone.<br>
<br>
Day wore into evening and soon my love said He had some bad news. &quot;Oh&quot;, I queried, &quot;tell me and I will try and see what I can do to help&quot;. He then said that he had been called to go on a mission for Mithanile Marr. Gently he explained that this may be a battle that he may not return from. &quot;What, No. You can't make me a widow so soon&quot; I protested. I knew that he would not have told me if there where some why for this not to be so. I conceded to that fact quickly and asked &quot;When Love, when must you go?&quot; &quot;That I don't know&quot; he said &quot;It could be tomorrow or in a week, but I must be ready when the call comes&quot;.<br>
<br>
He confessed that he had know of this news for some time and wished now he had told me sooner. I knew this burden must have been great for him to bear alone. I in my heart knew that he did not need a tearful,sorry, mournful wife. No he needed to have one that was strong and willing to let him do what it is that he must do. And so I comforted him and expressed my sorrow, lightly. Even though my heart was breaking, my world was crashing down around me, I knew that his leaving was inevitable. <br>
<br>
All I can do was thank Mother Tunare for allowing me this love if even for a short time. It is one that will carry me through my life. I again to soon will be alone, but I will always have his name and the sweet memories we share. As our time together grows short I will pray for him to return, in hopes that somehow, someway he will be save and return to me.<br>
<br>
We shared one adventure after another, special moments that only we two will know. <br>
